Made one of those Butterball boneless turkey breast roasts. The turkey came out okay, the "concentrated gravy " packet that came with it, not so good. Made mashed potatoes, the aforementioned mediocre gravy, microwavable frozen mixed vegetables, and dressing. Dressing was a mix from a box, with mushrooms, celery, and onion added to it. I couldn't find wild rice this year so I cooked some brown rice instead and stirred it in. Made some brownies--another mix from a box, but I added instant coffee to give them a chocolate mocha flavor, and stirred in coconut and dark chocolate chips. Made some buttercream frosting and spread it on top of them. If only I'd made a rotisserie chicken--then I could have gotten a vixen to pay a visit.

Anonymous Mon 26 Dec 2022 23:27:34 No.53285881 Report

Leftovers.
The day after a holiday, I usually cook up my own stuff. Doing a turkey breast, sweet mashed potatoes w/ some good stuff mixed in, and maybe a few other things.
>>53283332
Even for smaller pieces, tenting the bird will help the meat be moister and more tender.
Two other bits of advice: while I love the ease of some of the microwave veggie bags (particularly the steamers bags), experimenting with an air fryer or other methods will seriously level up your meals.
And for brown rice, get the bag. Most use a 2:5 rice/water ratio and ask for 35-45 minutes simmer time with a lid on. Drain the remaining liquid ten minutes before it's done without taking the lid off, and place the pot back on the stove. It's a great method for tougher rice varieties and comes out even tastier.

Ah, I did the turkey in a covered roasting pan. The veggies were an afterthought. I stuck them in the microwave as the timer was getting close for the turkey and dressing. The brown rice I cooked with a couple of chicken bouillon cubes. The dressing from a box is normally pretty salty but I was adding a bunch of stuff to it--a couple of chopped onions, about a pound of white button mushrooms, three or four minced celery stalks, all sauteed in butter--and in the past this has resulted in the salt and seasoning getting diluted.

Cooking is a hobby of mine that I normally only indulge when I have people to cook for. A friend of mine who died in 2018 would organize potlucks for local sci-fi and fantasy fans and other nerds a few times a year. At my last couple of jobs sometimes they'd announce an office potluck and I'd be the only one to show up with food. Cooking for myself is like singing in the shower, ya know?
